Now I understand. `Expr.init(E.Object, E.Object{}, loc)` uses `Data.Store.append` which uses the `ASTMemoryAllocator`. This is why TOML, JSON5, etc. all set up the `ASTMemoryAllocator` scope before calling the parser:

```zig
var ast_memory_allocator = bun.handleOom(allocator.create(ast.ASTMemoryAllocator));
var ast_scope = ast_memory_allocator.enter(allocator);


defer ast_scope.exit();
```

My INI parser needs to be called within an ASTMemoryAllocator scope too. The `INIObject.zig`'s `parse` function will set up the scope before calling `ini.parse(...)`, while the INI parser itself just uses `Expr.init(...)` which taps into the thread-local ASTMemoryAllocator. For `E.Object.put(allocator, key, expr)` and `E.Object.putString(allocator, key, value)`, these use the allocator for the BabyList append, so I need to pass the arena allocator from the scope.

In `ini.zig`, the allocator is the arena allocator, and the strings are slices into the source which remain valid for the duration. I'm noticing there seem to be multiple `Expr.init` implementations depending on context—one that creates objects directly from the allocator and another that uses `Data.Store.append`. Let me trace through the actual code structure to understand which version is the real public function versus any compile-time variants.

